08516nam a22013935i 9780691224893DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20211996nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912248937 a10.1515/97806912248932doi  a(DE-B1597)576340  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a305.2300aChildren and the Politics of Culture /ced. by Sharon Stephens. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©1996  a1 online resource (376 p.) :b18 line illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Studies in Culture/Power/History ;v1100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tCHILDREN AND THE POLITICS OF CULTURE -- tIntroduction Children and the Politics of Culture in "Late Capitalism" -- tPART ONE: CHILDREN AND CHILDHOODS AT RISK IN THE "NEW WORLD ORDER" -- tChapter One The Child as Laborer and Consumer: The Disappearance of Childhood in Contemporary Japan -- tChapter Two Have You Seen Me? Recovering the Inner Child in Late Twentieth-Century America -- tChapter Three Children's Rights in a Free-Market Culture -- tPART TWO: CHILDREN, CULTURAL IDENTITY, AND THE STATE -- tChapter Four Children in the Examination War in South Korea: A Cultural Analysis -- tChapter Five Children's Stories and the State in New Order Indonesia -- tChapter Six Children, Population Policy, and the State in Singapore -- tChapter Seven Youth and the Politics of Culture in South Africa -- tPART THREE: CHILDREN AND THE POLITICS OF MINORITY CULTURAL IDENTITY -- tChapter Eight "There's a Time to Act English and a Time to Act Indian": The Politics of Identity among British-Sikh Teenagers -- tChapter Nine Second-Generation Noncitizens: Children of the Turkish Migrant Diaspora in Germany -- tChapter Ten Children, Politics, and Culture: The Case of Brazilian Indians -- tChapter Eleven The "Cultural Fallout" of Chernobyl Radiation in Norwegian Sami Regions: Implications for Children -- tPART FOUR: THE RECOVERY AND RECONSTRUCTION OF CHILDHOOD? -- tChapter Twelve Recovering Childhood: Children in South African National Reconstruction -- tAppendix The United Nations Convention on the Rights of the Child -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe bodies and minds of children--and the very space of children--are under assault. This is the message we receive from daily news headlines about violence, sexual abuse, exploitation, and neglect of children, and from a proliferation of books in recent years representing the domain of contemporary childhood as threatened, invaded, polluted, and "stolen" by adults. Through a series of essays that explore the global dimensions of children at risk, an international group of researchers and policymakers discuss the notion of children's rights, and in particular the claim that every child has a right to a cultural identity. Explorations of children's situations in Japan, Korea, Singapore, South Africa, England, Norway, the United States, Brazil, and Germany reveal how children's everyday lives and futures are often the stakes in contemporary battles that adults wage over definitions of cultural identity and state cultural policies. Throughout this volume, the authors address the complex and often ambiguous implications of the concept of rights. For example, it may be used to defend indigenous children from radically assimilationist or even genocidal state policies; but it may also be used to legitimate racist institutions. A substantive introduction by the editor examines global political economic frameworks for the cultural debates affecting children and traces intriguing, sometimes surprising, threads throughout the papers. In addition to the editor, the contributors are Norma Field, Marilyn Ivy, Mary John, Hae-joang Cho, Saya Shiraishi, Vivienne Wee, Pamela Reynolds, Kathleen Hall, Ruth Mandel, Manuela Carneiro da Cunha, and Njabulo Ndebele.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aADVO advertisements.  aBobo (magazine).  aBrazilian Indians.  aConfucian tradition.  aFoucault, Michel.  aGobind Singh.  aHuman Rights Commission (UN).  aKeynesianism.  aabortion.  aaddiction.  aadoption.  aapartheid.  aautomatic writing.  ablack racial experience.  abureaucracy (state).  acapitalism.  achild care centers.  achoice ideology.  acolonialism.  acultural markers.  aculture conflict.  ademocracy.  adepoliticalization.  adevelopment (child).  adomestic violence.  aeducation.  aemotional illness.  aenculturation.  aethnocentrism.  afamilism.  afashion or apparel.  aguardianship.  ahandicapped children.  ahigher education.  aideology.  aindigenous leaders.  ainner-child therapies.  aintersubjectivity.  ajuvenile delinquency.  aleft brain stimulation.  aliving conditions.  amarginalized children.  amaster narratives.  amulticulturalism.  anational identity.  anational security.  aotherness.  apatriarchal culture.  apatrilineality.  apeer relations.  apolitics of culture.  aracial minorities.1 aCho, Hae-joang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aField, Norma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, Kathleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIvy, Marilyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohn, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMandel, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNdebele, Njabulo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReynold